< review>
I have been going through the tedious process to get a nerve ablation since March/April 2015. I had the first diagnostic at the end of May. I was told at that time that there would be ONE diagnostic nerve block and then I would have the actual ablation done. It was not until my follow-up appointment after the first block that I was told there would be a second diagnostic block done before the nerve ablation. So, I had to wait for insurance approval for the second block, which finally came through in the beginning of July. I called immediately to make an appointment, which I expected to be for July. I was told at that time that the doctor was on vacation for July and that I would have to wait an entire month more and have it done Aug 20. Note that the more time this is pushed back, the more time I have to spend on disability and light duty for work. I finally get the second nerve block done Aug 20 and I was never given a follow up appointment date and time. The first time they sent me a letter in the mail with my follow up appointment on it (they told me it was on one date when it was actually scheduled for the day after), but nothing was sent to me for this one. I was unable to call until today because of work, so when I called today I was told that my appointment was for this past Tuesday. I missed it. So now on top of all of that, they just absolutely cannot fit me in until SEPTEMBER 28!! So now my procedure is being pushed back yet another month. If the timeline works the same as the last one did, I will be lucky to have the nerve ablation done some time in December or even January of 2016! It should not take 8 months to get a simple procedure done. I should not have to jump through so many hoops for pain relief. I have been dealing with this chronic back pain for many years. I was previously told by the same doctor a couple years ago that there was nothing else they could do for me. Now that they have finally decided to actually do something for me, it is taking most of a YEAR to get it done. That makes at least 2 months of time added on to the timeline solely because of problems with scheduling at the doctor's office. I think this is absolutely unacceptable that they cannot fit me in sooner for a 5 minute appointment that doesn't even require them to lay a finger on me. It could be done on the phone for goodness sake! And on top of all of that, the staff was rude, claimed that the doctor could not call me to speak to me on the phone (doctors call patients all the time) and the office manager is out of the office and cannot call me back until at least Monday. The first person I spoke to said she had no idea when the office manager would be able to call me back. It would be just "some time in the future." It is hard enough dealing with life altering, debilitating pain without the added stress of reams of red tape to cut through that shouldn't be there. I told them I am perfectly happy to wait in the office for hours if I have to in order to be seen. I don't care if I have to sit there all day, it just needs to be done NOW, not in a MONTH.< /review>

< Text>
I absolutely love this place! The food, the drinks, the service, right down to the nightclub upstairs. La Rosa has a great happy hour. I always brag about their wings, and margaritas! (I don't even drink tequila and I don't really like margaritas usually) All the times I have gone upstairs for the nightclub, there is always a fullhouse but still enough room to dance your heart out. There is never any drama or conflicts that get out of hand, like I've seen in the past at other clubs in Santa Rosa. Last Rosa is always a good time whether just to grab something to eat or a night out dancing.</Text>

< Name>
Lorraine S<//Name>
<Date>1548960620426</Date><rating>3< /rating>< Text>
The only reason I am giving this place any stars truly is because this is the ONLY night club Santa Rosa. If you want to dance with a dance floor, DJ, and a bar this is your only option in Santa Rosa. Some people can argue that Stout brothers counts but the open floor space is so small it fits about 10 people at a time and you run into people ordering drinks every 3 seconds and it is infuriating. It's already infuriating enough if you want to dance with your girlfriends and be interrupted by drunk men but it's worse in highly visible less dense spaces. Therefore, La Rosa's Lounge is the only real option for this. Their drinks are highly over priced for lacking alcohol but I think they are hoping you are already drunk enough without being able to distinguish the high nonalcoholic beverage to alcohol ratio if you like mixed drinks. So, I would suggest getting beers. The music is pretty good and you can check their facebook because selection depends on the DJ. I hate some of the electro music DJs because I am not a rave/jump up and down person. If that were the case I would go to a rave. I go here to dance and that usually means hip hop, R&B, and rap (MAYBE some pop). Oh, if you are a male, you have to wear collars in order to get in. Unless you are friends with the bouncers then they will let you pass.</Text>

<review>I want to start by saying I loved the view. From the moment you walk in, you imagine you will have a great experience. We had a reservation, so when we walked to the main lobby we were told to wait a couple of minutes. After a few minutes a waiter came around and asked us to follow her. She asked if we were celebrating any special occasion, I told her "yes, anniversary", and she congratulated us. We followed her through the building to the main yard, and went all the way to the lower courtyard. My first impression was that the building was beautiful, the courtyard was even more pretty with all the pretty Valley lights and nice setting. However, the lower courtyard had plastic tables that really took away from the fancy dinner I expected. Regardless, we sat by one of the middle tables for 4, even though we were just 2, with a half view of the Valley and a very empty looking plastic table. We ordered 2 New York Steaks and a few drinks. After one hour of waiting, the nice waiter came around with our orders. We asked for well done steaks and got medium rare. My husband's steak was semi-cold. The mashed potatoes got my 5 stars, it was one of the best mashed potatoes I have ever had at a restaurant. The drinks were nice too, I had a mimosa and a margarita. Both were good, just very low on alcohol, but I was glad about that. For the very expensive dinner I was honestly expecting a grand occasion, but neither the food nor the location was up to my dreamed anniversary dinner.
Overall it was a nice experience, I don't think I will be coming back anytime soon. Next time, if I ever come back, I will try the main building and hopefully get my well done steaks.<//review>< pics>

<user_id>110622116580981631449</user_id><username>Sarah Ouigue</username><Date>1613712355491<//Date>< Rating>

< Text>
Food was good -well some of it, but I didn't think is was for the prices. However, I had agreed to go there to pick up food for Valentine's day as my husband loves prime rib. When ordering he requested to swap out his sides for a baked potato, so I asked the same for french fries. We drove from Hollywood to collect our special dinner however I realised I too had a baked potato. I didn't think much of it at first. I'm a pescatarian so I had ordered the salmon, very small compared to my husband's steak. Then I realised the potatos were covered in thick chunks of bacon, trying not to make a big deal of it as I didn't want to ruin my husband meal I removed the bacon. Unfortunately after undressing my potato I could see it had dark almost black marks through out the vegetable. Really very underwhelmed at the experience but at least my husband enjoyed his steak.</Text>

<userid>111659278288320583219</userid><review>Odyssey is a fun restaurant with a great view.  The actual restaurant part of the property lines the front window over looking the valley.  It is very similar to the pre-renovated castaway's in Burbank if you've ever been there.  We had the salmon, filet mignon, and the prime rib.  The salmon was excellent, but both the filet and prime rib were overcooked and under seasoned.  They give lots of bread while you wait which is nice but the butter is unsalted so grab that salt shaker.  All of their potatoe sides were very good.  Their other sides weren't as good.  They have a non-alcoholic drink with lemonade and strawberry that was awesome.  Overall it was a little pricey for the quality of food and the inside is looking a little older, but it is in a great location with a pretty decent array of items on the menu.  I would go again.<//review></record>

Amazing view of San Fernando Valley, particularly at night.  Located just west of 405 Fwy and north of 118 Fwy.  Sunday brunch is $49, but a wide variety of choices and everything you can imagine from beef, sea food, fruits, salads, omelet bar, deserts, beverages.  Staff is OK.  Ambience is very nice.  Enjoyable to just sit outside near fire pit and talk.  Has valet parking, but also plenty of self parking.</review>

<time>1531431502657<//time><Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
Amazing place. Phenomenal view. Incredible dessert. Easy reservations.
The calamari was hailed as one of the best. I got it, expecting only calamari... But no, there are actually LITTLE TINY BABY WHOLE SQUIDS, along with the standard calamari. they should state that on the menu. Seeing those little babies, deep fried in batter basically made me sick and ashamed. No one wants to be reminded they're hurting something by eating!! I didn't eat those, obviously.
Our servers were.....just okay...they seemed a little pre occupied and inattentive for my taste as it took 15 minutes until we were able to order. Maybe that one server had a bad day. No matter though, still a five star place, hands down.
It's truly eco friendly that they grow all their own produce on the mountain that the restaurant is on top of!<//Review>

<date>1563068042264< /date>< Text>
I honestly tried this place a couple of times before I did this review.  This place has been slowly declining year by year and it is a true disappointment. Beautiful views but awful food. So this review is regarding my recent visit on Wednesday, December 12 for the buffet lunch. Now, this brunch was $32 all you can eat and $4.50 for a soda. The first problem was the food was overcooked and dry, especially the meats. Flavor was weak and the taste was bland. The next issue was it was all you can eat, but they did not refill the food. I was basically eating leftovers! What was ridiculous was the crabs, there were only small scraps when I got there, so I decided to ask the server if there will be more crabs. The gentleman took the tray and said he will bring some more out, half an hour later, NOTHING! As for the clam chowder, the pot was completely sizzling with the dry remains in it. Now the desert I was expecting to be at least decent, but it was not! Again nothing was left and nor did they think they should put more out. Now for the chocolate roll log cake, there were little flies all over it. YUCK! I was there to celebrate an achievement but unfortunately, we picked the wrong place to celebrate. My family was going to do the Christmas brunch here, but due to the last visit, my husband changed the venue. True waste of money.< /Text>

< Text>
My wife and I celebrated our first wedding anniversary at the Odessy Thursday night and are so happy we did.
Walking in was breathtaking....the view of the city lights set the stage. We were greeted kindly by the hostess and seated immediately, which was great because the place was packed with people. Our server Donnie was incredible. He was professional and personnel and made us feel special. He made many recommendations which we went with. We started with mojitos which were great but dove into a sampler plate with prime rib tacos and calamari that was so tasty. Donnie recommended the salmon for my wife and a rib eye for myself as I was hungry. The wines he paired were perfect and the entrees were some of the best we have ever had.
Five stars to the Odessy......we will see you for the buffet on Sunday. It's our new spot<//Text>

< review>
This a must visit at some point if you live in the valley area. The views are absolutely gorgeous. Personally I prefer the bar area over the sit down restaurant or the patio. It is a great place to head to right before sunset so you get the sunset and the gorgeous twinkle of the valley. On a clear day you can see ridiculously far. I have also attended a number of events here and the food/organization of the event was great. It is not he newest/more over the top glamorous venue but it is solid, established and there won't be surprises here. I have been here in Jean and in formal attire and the venue has the ability to morph depending on the occasion.<//review>

<rating>4</rating>< text>
I was brought to Odyssey for a surprise birthday brunch. There was a reservation for 2, but upon arrival, the greeter couldn't find it. However, the greeter made things work and we were seated within 10 minutes.

I took a gander around the buffet before I piled up. There were a lot of options ranging from sushi to fresh seafood (clams, crab legs, and shrimp) to meat to breakfast items. Basically, there's something for everyone. My favorites included the breakfast potatoes and the clams. There was even a custom-made omelet bar!

After all that eating, how could I not make more room for dessert?! Lots of varieties of desserts, but my favorite was the make your own chocolate covered strawberries/pineapples/etc station.

There's a staff member that takes complimentary photos, prints on the spot, and the option to buy the bigger size.

Overall, I had a great birthday brunch experience here and I hope I can come back at night time to take in the beautiful skyline view.</text>

<Text>I've been a fan of the Odyssey's Sunday Brunch for years. There's no better way to prime a lazy Sunday morning than eating with friends, family or parents. The serving staff is always courteous and attentive, the food is varied and savory, and the view is unparalleled. It's well worth the drive out.

When looking at venues for a small (<100 guests) wedding, I was constantly stumped by overblown prices at other locales. The Odyssey's special events planners presented to me a package that was quite simply unmatchable. They included a buffet-style dinner with remarkable food and a dessert cart with coffee and pastries towards the evening's end, at a fraction of the cost that other venues had presented to me. My wife and I sprang for an open bar and a chocolate fountain for a little more. Even then, the price was spectacular. The Odyssey's staff was very easy to work with, and the day of the event they provided our guests with matchless service. The food was so well received that my guests still -- 3 years after the event-- rave about their meal and drinks that night.

Consider the Odyssey for your next big event. You won't be disappointed!</Text><Date>1457228687944</Date><name>Alex Martinez<//name><response>None</response><Pics>None<//Pics><rate>5</rate></record></dataset><record>

< text>
My wife and I dined here yesterday for the first time to celebrate our 3 year anniversary. The location of the restaurant was on a hilltop which provided some great views of the SF valley. We started out seated on the patio, amazing view of the valley @ 530. Didn't last long as clusters of flying pests/bugs around our table didn't allow us to enjoy the ambience of dining outside. The hostess gladly moved us to a table inside.

Our server Shannon took great care of us! I ordered the filet mignon/lobster tail while my wife had the Polynesian shrimp/lobster tail. The wild berry mojito was excellent!  Our only complaint was that the kitchen forgot my wife's lobster tail with her entree & the food didn't come out very hot. More on the lukewarm side. My wife finished her meal before her lobster tail finally arrived. That was disappointing. She still enjoyed her lobster tail & glass of wine. The manager apologized for the lateness of the lobster tail, comp'd it along with our drinks & gave us a dessert as well.

We'll be back to dine here. Hopefully issues with the kitchen will be a thing of the past. Our server Shannon was great! Thank you Shannon!<//text>

<Rating>1< /Rating><Review>Came for a large birthday party. We were sat outdoors. The table tops were all wobbly. Not due to uneven ground, but due to the tops themselves coming loose from the base.

Those 2 tables stayed dirty with dishes and champagne bottles on them, and the broken glass stayed on the ground for the rest of the night. While walking around the area, we had to kick the glass under the table to keep people from stepping on it.
While waiting for service several people got up for smoke breaks. As we walked around we noticed Gatorade bottles, glasses, cups, rags, napkins, on the walkways and in the bushes.
After STILL not receiving service our birthday girl got up TWICE to go find a waitress. When we finally ordered, the waitress took our orders on a piece of folded up, used, printer paper. Not even proper tickets.
3 people ordered salads, nothing more. Those salads came out LONG before anyone else's food, so they just sat there waiting for everyone else to get their food. Once everyone finally got their food I was almost finished with my plate when one person at the end of the table finally got his plate that had been forgotten.
After dinner, several us had to go to the front desk 2 and 3 times to try and get a server to bring our check. We asked for our check while the sun was still up, we didn't leave until well after the sun was down.

It was my wifeâ€™s Bday last night on Friday. We were planning to visit Odyssey for a while, finally opportunity became a reality:) We live 5 min away from this joint. So, 3 adults and 3 kids... I got the reservation for 8:30 pm. We were few min early. This place was half empty.
Very old looking restaurant, reminded me of Yamashiro in Hollywood. Pretty much a branch muncher. We sat down, after half an hour they brought us 4 pieces of bread with a butter and lemonade for kids. Tap water was so disgusting, my wife asked me to bring our water bottle from the car. We ordered few dishes from the limited to nothing menu, and started to wait for our food:) pretty much everyone else in a restaurant was doing the same thing. Some tables I saw kids trying to fall asleep on their chairs, but we tried to cheer up each other for the upcoming delicatessens:))) around 10:30 pm food was served.... my daughter was crying, she was so hungry, waiting for macaroni and cheese.
She got her two table spoons of yellow mess called macaroni. Very cheerful waiter was trying so hard to make it fun.
We finished our meals and waited another half and hour for deserts. Half of my short ribs was a plain fat, which I successfully spitted back on my plate. The intimate atmosphere requires everyone to use their phones flashlight in order to read the menus. We got few boxes to go and headed home. <userid>103548480098803434561<//userid>< Review>
This was honestly one of the best eating experiences I've ever had. They had so many options and so much food not to mention bottomless mimosas (and when I say bottomless I mean the waiter or waitress is constantly filling it before you get the chance to finish it). They have a waffle station as well as an omelet and pasta station where they make it for you fresh. They also have fresh oysters and shrimp as well. staff is extremely friendly and attentive whether they're you're server or not. The wait for the Sunday brunch was extremely reasonable (20 minutes with no reservation). Definitely will be coming back here to celebrate another anniversary. Definitely an enjoyable eating experience whether you're with your spouse or your family.< /Review>

There isn't anything extra done, well maybe a few flowers, and you don't get anything extra; you just get to pay more.  I used to go regularly until I happened to go on one of those special days and had no idea until they brought the check. < user_id>
101546071429892343378<//user_id>
< name>
Jesus Beltran<//name>
<date>1489717258186< /date>< rating>
3</rating>
< Text>
I wanted to take my girlfriend somewhere very special and nice for her birthday. It was easy to to reserve a table for two that day right over the phone. A really nice lady booked my reservation and answered the questions I had. Parking was easy, we were seated rather quickly, and the staff was very nice. The restaurant has a pretty nice view of the valley. When we got there the restaurant had a many open tables but the bar was very busy. It wasn't so bad on a Thursday night.
Our waiter attended us quickly with our menus and asked for drinks. Minutes later he brought our appetizer. When it came to our entrees, we ordered, but did not receive anything until many minutes later. We had finished our appetizers, drank almost all our drinks, and had finish taking pictures of the occasion. We were starting to get very impatient and wondering if they were even working on our food. 45 minutes later we finally received our food, and I had in mind that they had done somthing to perfect the food because of the time it took, but it was sad say the food was average-at-best. The taste was nothing but ordinary, and to be honest the lobster was a little overcooked and chewy.
So the main dishes weren't all that fantastic, but later came the free birthday dessert which was the comeback of the night. I've got to say that the desserts at The Odyssey do not disappoint. Her birthday brownie with ice cream on top and powdered sugar was one of the best we've ever had! And I've got to say the creme brulee wasn't so bad either.
Overall the restaurant is pretty good but if you're looking for something jaw dropping, mouth-watering, and price worthy, I suggest you keep looking. As for drinks you're very limited to just alcoholic drinks and/or water. My girlfriend and I decided it was sadly a once-in-a-lifetime visit and we don't believe we will be going back anytime soon.</Text>

<GmapID>0x80c29011ba9d643d:0xa5ea6e4db9be3f1e< /GmapID>< review>
I am wishing I could rate Odyssey as 5-star. How sad that they took an excellent view and classic wood-paneled restaurant and added poorly cooked food that is geared for catering large events. Look, rubbery shrimp, raw filets, and boring boiled red potatoes do not have a place in this restaurant. Contemporize the menu and cook food correctly. How about adding some salt, which was sorely missing? Again, okay for a wedding reception; not acceptable for a classy, romantic restaurant.

One reviewer commented about the state of repairs. We walked past a chair with the back so loose that it is an injury in the making. Staff need to report broken chairs and management needs to fit them.  This was the only repair issue we saw.

Service... hoo hum, but at least replaced the over-cooked shrimp with some that were edible.

Other than that, a great view. 5-star view and setting with 2-star food. There is potential for great restaurant, if the owners realize that their restaurant guests are at least as important as the big catering events that are hosted in other rooms.<//review>

115069608137739210825</UserId.>
< Name>
Vindy Buziashvili<//Name>
< date>
1516982415467<//date>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
The Odyssey is a hilltop restaurant overlooking the San Fernando Valley in Los Angeles County, California. It has wonderful food, but more importantly, the ambiance makes it special. At night you can see the entire valley laid out before you like a pile of jewels. There is a firepit out on the patio where you can eat al fresco if you want. The service is prompt, the wait staff is friendly and helpful. I went there on a first date with my future husband, and it was the most romantic, wonderful time. We closed the place down, staying till almost 2am. We had bacon wrapped filet minon with steamed vegetables, and tiramisu for dessert. It's a dinner I will never forget, because of the romance, the atmosphere, and the beautiful view of the Valley below us on a clear cool night.</Review>

<date>1429114422496</date><Rate>3< /Rate>< UserId.>
100206180131731784292</UserId.>
<pics>None</pics>< text>
This isn't really a place you come for food but you come for the view.

We went for date night and it was very romantic with the view outside.  The food was just OK.

The Buffalo Shrimp appetizer was very good.  I got prime rib, medium rare, and my boyfriend got the cowboy ribeye. My prime rib came medium well to well done and I think had it not been for that it would have been pretty good. But, for me, it was dry.  The augratin potatoes were delicious though and I love that they have their own farm on prem.

In another review I saw someone complain that you couldn't taste the food because it was all too salty.  I get that review but for me the salt was great.  I liked not having to add any additional and I didn't feel it was too overwhelming.

I think we would for sure go back again, as the food wasn't bad just wasn't amazing, for the view.  On a nice warm summer night it would be great to sit out on the patio.< /text>

< Name>
Brad Hori<//Name>
<date>1485273315364< /date><rate>3< /rate>< review>
A little run down?
That's what I heard from someone else too.
We went for a company party.
Have not been there in 8 years.
We (my wife and I) were not impressed.
We went 2 hours early and sat in the bar.
Yeah, the views were great, but the appetizers were not.
We waited a long time to get the appetizers. They brought us the wrong order at first. They took that back. Wonder if they served it to someone else since it was already delivered to us? I can go into details but I don't think it will matter at this time. Good thing we got there early!
Once in the party, they served appetizers. The chicken was a little dry.
Once the buffet started, I was not to impressed with the food. The prime rib was ok, but seemed a little overcooked, as it melted in your mouth ( I do mean melted!). Now, I smoke meats at home, and I know when something is that soft that its over cooked! The Au Gratin Potatoes were not very good, and very hard to cut into the top. The salmon was ok. The chicken just ok too.
Everything just seem to be Ok, as the 3 stars show, 2.5 stars if I could give it a 1/2 star!
As a comparison, our other holiday parties at other locations were a whole lot better, and I didn't think one was that great, but heck, it was a whole lot better than this!</review>
